Such an expression as ut est natura invidiae, though it may of course be paralleled from other writers, has a sort of family likeness to quae natura pauoris est, Hist. iii. 84, 2ο ; cupidine ingenii humani libentius obseura credendi, ib. i. 22, 16; ut ferme acerrima proximorum odia sunt, ib. iv. 70, 12, and many other phrases familiar to students of Tacitus. The closing deliverance of Maternus, ch. 41 ad fin. nunc, quoniam nemo eodem tempore adsequi potest numnam famam et magnam quietem, bono saeculi sui quisque citra obtrectationem alterius utatur reminds the reader of the famous utterance in the Agricola (42, 18) sciant quibus moris est inlicita me'rari', posse etiam sub malis principibus magnos uiros csse, obsequiumque ac modestiam, si industria ac nigror adsint, eo laudis escendere quo plerique per abrupta, sed in nullum reipublicae usum, ambitiosa morte inclaruerunt. The sentiment of acquiescence in the necessity for the rule of a single man, which finds expression in this closing speech, is another clement in the identification: the whole pohtical tone¹ is quite consistent with that which we know was adopted by Tacitus. Again, that feeling of regret for th'e past which seems to have entered into the very composition of the historian's genius is exemplified in the poet-pleader’s first speech (11-13), with its beautiful picture of a golden age (cp. Ann. iii. 26). But it is in the sphere of moral sentiment that the resemblance is most pronounced. Messalla’s lament over the obliuio moris antiqui (28. 6) is fitly put into his mouth by the writer who made even his Germania an opportunity for introduc· ¹ ing weighty reflections on the moral decadence of Rome.
